<paragraph id="3340217A40075F2CFCD4FB7A4BAB3D47" blockId="16.[806,1421,1264,1317]" pageId="16" pageNumber="283">
<emphasis id="018BFD6840075F2CFCD4FB7A4CC03D67" box="[806,932,1264,1285]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="283">Etymology:</emphasis>
The name ‘ 
<emphasis id="018BFD6840075F2CFBC4FB7A4BF33D67" box="[1078,1175,1264,1285]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="283">barbara’</emphasis>
is descriptive of the name of one of my daughters (EGH).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3340217A40075F2CFCD4FACB4CF53F66" blockId="16.[806,1422,1344,1796]" pageId="16" pageNumber="283">
<emphasis id="018BFD6840075F2CFCD4FACB4C8D3D34" box="[806,1001,1345,1366]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="283">Taxonomic notes:</emphasis>
The entirely black gena, mesonotum with narrow yellow vittae, triangular surstylus, and hypandrium with lateral projections distinguish 
<taxonomicName id="F4FF5AF940075F2CFCD4FA174CFB3DD3" authorityName="Rotheray &amp; Hancock &amp; Marcos-García" authorityYear="2007" box="[806,927,1436,1458]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Copestylum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="283" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="barbara">
<emphasis id="018BFD6840075F2CFCD4FA174CFB3DD3" box="[806,927,1436,1458]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="283">C. barbara</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<taxonomicName id="F4FF5AF940075F2CFC0BFA164A6A3DD3" authorityName="Rotheray &amp; Hancock &amp; Marcos-García" authorityYear="2007" box="[1017,1294,1436,1457]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Copestylum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="283" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="elizabethae">
<emphasis id="018BFD6840075F2CFC0BFA164A6A3DD3" box="[1017,1294,1436,1457]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="283">Copestylum elizabethae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the only other species in this subgroup. The colour pattern of the abdominal tergites are also distinctive among tank group species, and are only shared with 
<taxonomicName id="F4FF5AF940075F2CFB00FA734AE33E6F" authorityName="Rotheray &amp; Hancock &amp; Marcos-García" authorityYear="2007" box="[1266,1415,1528,1550]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Copestylum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="283" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="xalapensis">
<emphasis id="018BFD6840075F2CFB00FA734AE33E6F" box="[1266,1415,1528,1550]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="283">C. xalapensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but this species lack a medial vitta on the face. Subgroup Elizabethae early stages are distinguished from other tank subgroups by the complete marginal band and lappets incorporated into it. The early stages of 
<taxonomicName id="F4FF5AF940075F2CFCD4F9184CFB3EC5" authorityName="Rotheray &amp; Hancock &amp; Marcos-García" authorityYear="2007" box="[806,927,1682,1703]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Copestylum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="283" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="barbara">
<emphasis id="018BFD6840075F2CFCD4F9184CFB3EC5" box="[806,927,1682,1703]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="283">C. barbara</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are readily distinguished from 
<taxonomicName id="F4FF5AF940075F2CFAE5F9184C333EA7" authorityName="Rotheray &amp; Hancock &amp; Marcos-García" authorityYear="2007" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Copestylum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="283" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="elizabethae">
<emphasis id="018BFD6840075F2CFAE5F9184C333EA7" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="283">C. elizabethae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the vestiture of the anal segment consisting of papillae with a crenate rim (
<figureCitation id="ABC43DFF40075F2CFB98F9454BDC3E87" box="[1130,1208,1743,1765]" captionStart="Figures 86–92" captionStartId="34.[142,232,1732,1751]" captionTargetBox="[199,1368,204,1690]" captionTargetId="figure-143@34.[193,1371,196,1700]" captionTargetPageId="34" captionText="Figures 86–92. Third stage larvae of Copestylum. 86. Copestylum lousiae, whole larva, head to the right, ventral view, length = 14 mm. 87. Copestylum tapia, whole larva, head to the right, dorsal view, length = 11 mm. 88. Copestylum barbara, crenate papillae from the dorsal surface of the anal segment. 89. Copestylum xalapensis, dentate spicules from the anterior fold of the prothorax. 90. Copestylum mamorum, vestiture of stout setae from the dorsal surface of the second abdominal segment. 91. Copestylum louisae, vestiture of long, fine setae from the dorsal surface of the second abdominal segment. 92. Copestylum puyarum, tapering spicules from the anterior fold of the prothorax." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5429874" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5429874/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="283">Fig. 88</figureCitation>
) and orange pupal spiracles.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3340217A40075F2CFCD4F8954B7B3F10" blockId="16.[806,1422,1823,1906]" pageId="16" pageNumber="283">
<emphasis id="018BFD6840075F2CFCD4F8954CE53F56" box="[806,897,1823,1844]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="283">Biology:</emphasis>
Adults were reared from larvae in water tanks of bromeliads (
<taxonomicName id="F4FF5AF940075F2CFBD6F8B44BA63F36" box="[1060,1218,1854,1876]" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="16" pageNumber="283" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Bromeliaceae</taxonomicName>
), and are known only from 
<collectingCountry id="4BE861EA40075F2CFC6EF8D74B7F3F10" box="[924,1051,1884,1906]" name="Costa Rica" pageId="16" pageNumber="283">Costa Rica</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
